sols_latex:
To classify the critical points, we use the second derivative test.

From $f_x = ye^y + x$, we compute:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f_{xx} = 1
\end{align*} and

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f_{xy} = e^y + y e^y = e^y (1+y)
\end{align*}

From $f_y = xe^y (y+1)$, we find:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle
f_{yy} = x [e^y (y+1) + e^y] = xe^y (y+2)
\end{align*}

Hence,

\begin{align*}
D = f_{xx} f_{yy} - f_{xy}^2 = xe^y (y+2) - e^{2y}(1+y)^2
\end{align*}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  At (0,0), we find $D = 0-1 = -1 < 0$. As $D < 0$, we have a
  \textbf{saddle point}.
\item
  At $(e^{-1},-1)$, we find $D = e^{-2} -0 > 0$, so there is either a
  local maximum or local minimum. From $f_{xx}(e^{-1},-1) = 1 > 0$, it
  must be a \textbf{local minimum}.
\end{itemize}

